Lora closed her eyes and spoke of their father, Brian Shahnra.  She talked about his smile, his strength, and the happiness he brought her and Merrie.  Greeneyes knew then why she felt sadness and loss when he died.<br>
<br>
“He gave you something…that night.”  She prompted.<br>
“My necklace.”  Lora fumbled at her dress and pulled up the chain and locket.  “He said he loved me.  He said to always-“<br>
“-Make the right choices,” Greeneyes finished.  “And I failed him.”  She closed her eyes to staunch the tears and failed.  “Daddy, I failed you.  Forgive me.”  She put her head in her hands and dropped to her knees.  Lora came closer and almost touched her.<br>
“But you’re here now.  Somehow.  A second chance, you said.”<br>
“But I’m failing!  I try to control my magic, and when it matters the most I fail!”  She looked up for the answers she knew the girl did not have.  “People keep dying.  Father, Mother…Mara, the witches.  It’s all happened before!  I can’t control it and I keep finding the path I walked before!”  Greeneyes shook her head violently.  “I don’t know where to go now Lora.  I’m lost.  I’m here to save you somehow and I can’t even save myself!”  She pounded her fists on her thighs.<br>
<br>
She couldn’t stand to see Greeneyes this way.  Lora needed her to be strong.  “Why did you ask about my necklace?”<br>
Greeneyes answered cautiously.  She didn’t want to think about the young woman whose face she saw screaming in pain.  “I saw it in one of my dreams.  Why did he give it to you on that night?  Why would I remember it, unless…”<br>
“Unless he knew something was going to happen.  He was sad.  I still remember his sadness when he gave it to me.”  She turned the pendant over in her hands.  “I’ve never taken it off.  I haven’t thought about it for so long.”  She popped it open.  “Daddy, Mommy.”  Lora looked through tears at the pictures within and touched them longingly with her fingertips.<br>
“May I?”  Greeneyes gently motioned for the pendant and Lora passed it to her.<br>
Their fingers did not touch, but as the pendant passed from one hand to the next they heard his voice.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>’My dearest daughter Loreana.  Love of my life.  I wish that this day had not come.  I wanted to say goodbye so badly but I didn’t want to frighten you.”<br>
I failed, very long ago, and bargained my life to my god so that you would have a second chance in your life if you ever needed it.  The second chance I never got at destroying an evil that I knew would come for me…and you…eventually.  When I saw that woman at festival today, I knew that your second chance was already upon you, in a way more terrible yet more awesome than I ever could have imagined.  Find the one who could be your sister and never leave her side.  When you have found her, seek Barradurn of T’ro’adon in the city of Derek, Daerga Ka.”<br>
I don’t know what horrible twist of fate has brought us to this day and I wish I could guide you further.  I love you my dearest child.  Tell her I love her too.  Tell her…I am so very sorry.’</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
“It’s all my fault,” Greeneyes finally said.  Lora just hung her head, silently crying after hearing her father’s voice again.  “Anger was all I had, all I was.  I thought the power would solve everything.  I thought I could bring everything I had lost back.”<br>
Lora moved toward Greeneyes.<br>
“No, don’t.”<br>
“Yes.  I want to.  You can’t carry so much yourself.”<br>
“I have to Lora.  It’s my burden, my price.”<br>
Lora continued forward.  Greeneyes shied away.<br>
“No.  You don’t have to carry it all.  These are the choices I would have made if you were not here now.  Let me share it…please…I…I need to hold somebody.  I’m willing to pay for that.”  She brought her hand close to Greeneyes face.  It was shaking.<br>
“No,” Greeneyes whispered, but she wanted it too.  She felt so alone and so scared.  She looked up at Lora and, steeling herself, grabbed her in a fierce embrace that was returned just as strongly.<br>
<br>
Loreana opened her mind and heart to the nightmares and saw them for what they were.  The life Greeneyes lived as a price to save her life and her soul.  They held each other through the deluge until it finally receded, like the tide after a storm.  Lora then returned her own images and dreams.  Dreams of her father and mother, the friends she had in Miera Kiy, all of the happy moments they shared before tragedy swallowed her life.  Lora gave Greeneyes these memories so the woman would not feel so alone any more.  What happiness Loreana had in her life she willingly shared with her other self.<br>
<br>
“Pippen.”<br>
“Pippen?”<br>
“My love.  The one that brought me so much happiness while I was in Miera Kiy.”  The two women still held each other tightly.  Nothing could have separated them at that moment.  “I left him with Dundare after…” she took a deep, painful breath.  “After the gruagan almost killed him.”  She could feel Loreana’s heart beating with hers.  “It’s been two years and I never wrote him, never went to see him.  He said he’d stay by my side the whole way,” she let go now and stared downward, “and I abandoned him.”<br>
Lora stroked her hair gently.  “Then I think you should return to him,” she whispered.  <br>
Greeneyes nodded.  “I think Denan can help us as well.”  She saw he question on Lora’s face.  “Denan and Megda Ironland.  The two who took me in.  They’ve already helped me more than I could ever repay.”<br>
“Ironland.”  Lora grinned.  “That’s where you took your last name.”<br>
“It was the only thing I could think of.”<br>
“And Greeneyes?” the girl prompted.<br>
“Pippen.  When I couldn’t remember my own.”<br>
“L’ree.”<br>
“Sapphire L’ree.  A Wichta title and name.  The demon I couldn’t, and won’t, accept.”<br>
Lora smiled and brought her twin’s head to rest against her.  “Then Greeneyes Ironland it is.”<br>
Greeneyes shook her head.  “No.  Shahnra.  For my father.  For our father.”  Now she smiled.  “And for the little sister I have walked through fire to save.”  Her smile faded…If she could save her.<br>
<br>
They sat for a long while, until the sun rose again, holding hands and sharing memories until sleep overtook them.  They didn’t wake until midday.<br>
“We should be going.  There’s nothing for me here now,” Lora said quietly.<br>
“There’s one thing to do first.”  Greeneyes looked toward the house.  “You don’t have to…”<br>
“I want to.  I need to say goodbye.”<br>
<br>
The two women were silent as they accomplished the gruesome task.  They buried Mara by the small shrine to Gaervalen.  On the grave, Greeneyes placed the small plant that Mara had healed when they first met.  With Gaervalen’s magic, she lovingly coaxed its roots into the soil.  Holding Lora’s hand, she said a prayer of farewell to their friend.<br>
“Greeneyes!” Lora gasped.  “Look!”<br>
The small shrub, which had grown a bit since Mara’s healing touch, was now growing and blooming right before their astonished eyes.  They backed away, such was its rapid growth, and watched in amazement.<br>
“It’s beautiful,” Lora whispered.<br>
They watched as it extended branches across grave and shrine.  The plant did not grow tall, but wide like a bush.  Only three vine-like branches grew upwards, reaching for the sky.<br>
“Gaervalen,” Greeneyes whispered in awe.<br>
The three branches twisted around each other as they grew, forming an arrow-straight rod.  A foot above their heads the branches separated then began weaving in and out in a pattern of hooks and bends that finally joined, completing the sphere.<br>
The bush ceased its growth then as both women heard a voice like a whisper on the wind.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>’This path lies in my shadow Oerskolna.  Heed well your steps.’</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Not daring to breath, Greeneyes glanced at Lora then at the staff and reached for it.  The staff came off easily, as if the plant released its hold on the branches when her hand touched it.  As she brought it down to her side, the head flashed.  Her necklace, the one presented to her by Mara, flashed in response.  Greeneyes felt the necklace come alive.  A tickle ran up her neck and played on her left cheek before it was still again.  <br>
Lora reached up and turned Greeneyes’ head towards her.  “He’s marked you.”<br>
“What?”<br>
“Your cheek.  A pattern.  Like the head of the staff.  Mara didn’t have that.”<br>
They looked toward the grave and the shrine, both shrouded in branches and leaves.  Greeneyes ran her fingers across the faint lines of the symbol.  The same silent question passed between them.<br>
