<br>
They conducted the necessary business as quickly and discreetly as they could.  Greeneyes was not sure how many of the caeban had survived and where those survivors might be.  Lora wanted to say goodbye to Cess, but she agreed with her older self that even that would be dangerous.  Lora would have agreed to just about anything at the moment.  The girl was deeply depressed and would go hours without saying or doing anything.  Standing by her mother’s grave one eve, Lora finally released a small part of her bitterness in a silent, tearful goodbye.  That night, Greeneyes held Lora tightly until the girl drifted into her uneasy, nightmare-filled sleep.<br>
<br>
Greeneyes retrieved her dagger, the figurine and her money from the wreckage of Mara’s home.  The dagger was only slightly scorched on the hilt and sheath.  The figurine was blackened, but only over the woman’s body, leaving the child’s untouched.  Her money was safe, though the pouch had burned.  Both women purchased enough clothing and supplies to travel before setting off for Miera Kiy.<br>
The days of mid-fall had started to cool and the nights grow cold.  They left early in the morning, bundled up to ward off the evening’s chill, and said their last goodbye to that chapter in their lives.<br>
<br>
They walked to Tasserty.  Greeneyes said nothing as they passed the site where the ill-fated wagon train had stopped.  Lora saw her partner go silent and felt her sadness and anger at herself.  She made Greeneyes talk about Pippen and, after much persuasion, convinced her to sing one of the songs she and the bard loved.  Greeneyes cheered up somewhat and by the time they reached Tasserty they were both tired but in good spirits.<br>
Catching rides with merchants and travelers was an easy task.  Few could say no to the lovely pair of sisters and their travels were uneventful.  They reached Miera Kiy in good time, arriving a few days later.<br>
<br>
Greeneyes and Loreana waved goodbye to the gray-bearded, old merchant at the Miera Kiy sign-rock.  They had traveled with him from Kimbleton and thoroughly enjoyed his company.  He had a good story or amusing joke for almost everything they could imagine.  When they weren’t rolling in laughter they sat in rapt attention as he told stories of the old kingdoms or his younger travelling days and they were sorry to finally bid him farewell.  Offers of payments received only a shake of his head and his own thanks for their company.<br>
Lora looked to her companion after the merchant disappeared down the hill to Miera Kiy.<br>
“Dundare’s first,” Greeneyes replied to the unspoken question.<br>
<br>
The fallen tree where she and Pippen had been attacked had long been pushed into the riverbed.  Again the silent contemplation by Greeneyes had to be broken by Lora’s questions, this time about Dundare.<br>
The sun was touching the trees as they came in sight of the small home.  Smoke drifted lazily from the chimney and Dundare’s home radiated the same warmth she remembered from the past.<br>
“What’s wrong?” Lora asked when Greeneyes stopped, still a hundred paces from the door.<br>
“Nothing.  I was afraid he wouldn’t be there.”  She shrugged.  “I don’t know.”  Greeneyes continued walking to his doorway, Lora close behind.<br>
