Lora let Pippen take Greeneyes and approached the man, heeding Denan's warning not to approach too closely.  &quot;What do you know of a man named Bryan Shahnra?&quot;<br>
Harfred Gillmont couldn't see her, but when he heard her voice all will to fight left his body.  He was deathly afraid of the witch who had destroyed his guild.<br>
&quot;No-nothing.  Never heard of him.&quot;  His voice shook in fear.<br>
&quot;Oh?&quot;  She lowered her voice slightly.  &quot;Your companions here were also unable to answer.  Do you really desire to join the ignorant?&quot;<br>
Pippen shivered at the girl's tone.  Lora and Greeneyes were indeed connected, for better or worse.<br>
&quot;He...he was nobody.  Just a mark.&quot;<br>
&quot;He was my FATHER!&quot; she screamed.  Dundare couldn’t help but jerk at the sudden ferocity in her voice.<br>
Harfred strained to turn his head toward her voice, his eyes grew wide with fear when he saw her.  &quot;You!  The girl!&quot;<br>
Again she summoned the minor spell that had been so effective before.  She hoped it had similar effect now.<br>
&quot;Who ordered his death?&quot;<br>
The thief’s lip quivered, both eyes on the multi-hued green ball of magic.<br>
&quot;I...I don't know,&quot; he stammered.<br>
Lora brought the magic closer to his face.<br>
&quot;I don't!  He only told me hire somebody...somebody good.&quot;<br>
She drew closer, her hand inching towards his nose.  He tried desperately to slide away and was stopped by the Dwarf's knee slamming his face down again with an audible smack.<br>
“Here.  Let me try.”  Lora looked up to see Greeneyes’ weary face as she slowly walked into the thief’s view.  He began uttering nonsensical noises.  Greeneyes glared at him and he swore he saw her eyes flash green fire.<br>
<br>
<br>
Guildmaster of the Iron Key, Harfred Gillmont, looked up from his ledger with a scowl.  How the intruder had made it into his office without warning he didn’t know, yet somehow he did know that the dark haired stranger was not a threat…not to him.  Somebody would loose a hand for this though.<br>
“Who are-” Harfred’s words died on his lips when his eyes met those of the stranger.  Black in black.  He felt his strength and will drain from his body.<br>
“I have need of your services, Guildmaster,” the stranger said softly.<br>
“Wh-what,” Harfred cleared his throat and tried to regain some of his composure.  “What services would those be?”<br>
The man reached beneath his cloak and pulled out a gold coin.  The master thief’s eyes were naturally drawn to what he saw was a very old coin, worth far more than it’s face value.<br>
“I wish you to kill this man.”  He held the coin out on his open palm.  A pale mist slowly rose above it, and in the mist, a face.  “Bryan Shahnra.”<br>
Harfred was slightly annoyed the stranger did not take part in the word play that usually went along with transactions such as this.  Years of habit the thief now pushed aside.  He opened his mouth to speak and was cut off.<br>
“There is a woman, and a child.”  The images of a red haired woman and a brown haired child appeared in the mist.  “No harm is to come of them, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>especially the child.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> Is this understood?”<br>
Harfred nodded slowly.  Even if he wanted to protest, he couldn’t find the voice to do so.<br>
“I’m sure you know of one with the skills to handle his with discretion and competence.  Do not send one of your <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>thieves.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->” He stressed the word as if speaking of children.  “Two more things.  There is a symbol the man keeps around his neck.  Take this and keep it safe.  Someone will retrieve it.”  He paused a moment before continuing.  “Have your assassin deliver this message to his mark:  ‘The Avatar is come.  The Child of Shadow will be joined.’”<br>
A chill raced through the guildmaster’s body.  “It will be done.”<br>
The man with the midnight eyes reached into his cloak again and withdrew a small, heavy silk bag and dropped it on Harfred’s desk.  The thief knew by the dull clank that it held two gold bars.  The mint undoubtedly Torainian.  He didn’t move to retrieve them.<br>
“That should satisfy your greed.  Do not fail.”<br>
Harfred could only nod, and when the Master of the Iron Key blinked, the stranger with the black eyes was gone.<br>
<br>
<br>
Loreana was shaking.  Fear, anger, sadness, all fought for dominance.  Pippen grasped the girl by the shoulders and gently but insistently drew her away.  When he released her she stood there, her body still shaking and her gaze unfocused and distant.<br>
Greeneyes continued to stare at the Guildmaster.  “Now thief, my good friend there is going to loosen your bonds just enough for you to take me to the necklace.  No tricks, no traps, and I will let you live.”  She leaned towards the shaking man.  “But if I even think you’re twitching those fingers wrong, you will have a very long time to contemplate how you would rather be dead.”<br>
Harfred nodded slowly, the terror plain on his face.  Greeneyes nodded at Denan who untied then retied the cord as the assassin had bound Lora.<br>
Pippen and Dundare watched as the thief led them slowly to a door at the head of the hall.  As he reached for the panel next to the doorframe, Greeneyes laid her retrieved staff on his shoulder, causing him to jump.  “I’m deactivating a trap!  You almost caused me to spring it.”<br>
“That would have been unfortunate,” she whispered menacingly.  He nodded and the door opened with an audible click.<br>
<br>
Paintings, ornate statuary and finely carved woodwork decorated the large room the group entered.  Great shelves filled with bound texts and lacquered bookends lined the walls.  In the center, a huge teak desk and high-back cushioned chair completed the appearance of opulence and power.<br>
The Guildmaster walked around to the back of the desk.  Denan hopped up onto the desk, his boots creating dirty scratches in its polished surface.  Harfred’s squeak of protest was cut short by the point of Denan’s sword against his throat.<br>
“Carefully, Guildmaster.  No unfortunate accidents.”<br>
The thief thought better of what he was about to do, and slid his hand further to the left under the desk.  Another click and a small drawer popped open at the bottom of the desk.  Pulling out a small, brown cloth bag tied with a red string, he presented it to Greeneyes.<br>
“Open it and pour the contents onto the desk.”<br>
He did as he was told, hands shaking as he fumbled with the string and upturned the bag.  A large amulet and chain dropped to the desk.  “That’s it.  That’s all I have.  I’ve told you all I know.  Please let me go.”  His pitiful pleas were beginning to grate on Greeneyes nerves.<br>
Dundare took a step forward and waved his hand while whispering a word.  The guildmaster’s eyes rolled shut as he fell to the floor, his head thumping loudly on the desk as he fell.<br>
“Assuming he didn’t bang his head too hard, he should sleep soundly for a few bands,” Dundare said quietly.<br>
Lora slipped up beside the healer and grasped his hand as Pippen peered over her shoulder.  She then moved into the room and, looking towards Greeneyes and Denan, picked up the medallion and chain.  A tear fell from her eye as she clasped it tightly to her heart and closed her eyes.<br>
