<br>
Wordlessly, one of the six collapsed into the mud, chest heaving for breath, his young face twisted in pain.  A companion held a small flask of thick, clear liquid to his mouth.  The young woman, her black hair tied back revealing a pale but lovely face, held him up to her dingy breastplate and rocked him slowly, her leather and plated armor creaking in time.  She smiled briefly to give him the strength the potion could not.  The others kept silent vigil for long minutes as the young cleric regained some color in his face and finally signaled his readiness to continue.<br>
<br>
Eyes continually scanning the mists for the unliving guardians of the Black God, they continued on until the gray stones of the temple appeared suddenly before them.  Their wards had worked this far, the guardians had not been alerted by the destruction of the zombies further in the forest, but all were wary of the traps and all knew the unnatural creatures could strike at any time with the silent, single-minded determination of the undead.<br>
<br>
Reaching the wall of the structure, Fastag Morolen, the stocky, dark-haired dwarven priest of T’ro’adon, put his oversized warhammer at his belt and began moving along the stone, searching for the secret entrance he knew would be there.  The temple was built by dwarves after all.<br>
The High Priest of Dierguroth, Cruzaz Ror, had spell-slaved a small clan and set them to work building the God of Death’s shrine.  Forced to build a structure so inherently twisted and evil, the dwarves slowly died of sadness and despair, but not before they completed their own task.  They installed secret passages and doors that it’s vile inhabitants and their master knew nothing about.  Though they would not live to see it, they knew someday their kin would come and turn the temple against its master.  Fastag knew this as all his brothers knew, for the tale was held in the Stones, and he searched for the place that would give him passage.<br>
<br>
Forming a ring around the dwarven priest, the other five peered through the mists and above where the wall rose into the fog.  Though all were seasoned, the evil in the mists was so tangible, they had to continually fight off the feeling of utter hopelessness, the desire to give in to the silent voice of the fog.  Carlan Josh, the young human priest who had fallen, had only his faith in T’ro’adon the Stone God and the holy symbol he held in a death grip at his breast, to keep him going.  Jillian Corbet, another human and the warrior who had supplied the lifesaving potion to Carlan, silently recited the Seven Disciplines over and over while her eyes darted about at every imagined specter and ghost in the mists.  Miles Hardan, stoically silent and calm, seemingly unaffected by the will stealing haze, was in mental turmoil.  The way the fog warped sound and stole vision was driving him into an internal frenzy.  He longed for battle again so that his thoughts could be turned away from the intangible danger of the mist to the tangible bloodrush of the melee.<br>
<br>
Turning a corner as he continued his search along the stonework, Fastag leaped backward as a skeletal hand burst from the mud beneath the dwarf’s feet and grabbed his right boot with amazing strength.  The muddy skull of a long dead dwarf rose and snapped jagged teeth inches from the priest’s thigh.  Yelping in surprise, he scrambled for his hammer with one hand while delivering ill-aimed blows with the other.  Reaching the haft of the mithril and steel warhammer he gripped it in his broad hand and even as muscles tensed to swing the weapon he called ‘Stonesplitter’ another hammer of similar size but longer reach, came streaking down into the creature’s skull.  Bone fragments, mud, and rock exploded outward from the impact as the unholy bones were driven back into the ground.<br>
<br>
The dwarf looked up at the wielder of the hammer, Bryan, a young priest who had just been granted his title a month earlier.  His expression bespoke annoyance that the new priest though him incapable of handling a single undead.  In reality, the dwarf had been shocked at the suddenness of the attack and the dwarven features that had stared back at him.  The human read this in the older priest’s eyes but wisely kept to himself.  He also saw thanks in those eyes as the dwarf turned back to his probing.<br>
Dwarven High Priest Dalgoth Garun watched the silent exchange between his priests and thought about how well they worked together.  Each moved in compliment to the other.  He hoped they would do the same when it came time for the final step of the mission.  The High Priest turned his thoughts back inward as he contemplated what was ahead.<br>
<br>
Cruzaz Ror had come to these lands a century before and enslaved the children of T’ro’adon to do the work of Dierguroth.  This had angered the Stone God greatly, yet He had waited until now to direct His priests to action.  Perhaps time was no matter to the gods, or perhaps they waited for the proper time and circumstances for action.  Whatever the reason, Dalgoth’s faith in his Lord was unwavering and he knew that if he did all he had been directed to do, his small band would succeed.<br>
The task set forth for them though was not easy by any means.  After traversing the deadly forest and fighting the mists, they would have to gain entrance to the temple.  If indeed Fastag was right and his kin had built secret entrances into the temple, their mission had a better chance of succeeding than if they had to find a way in themselves.<br>
Once inside, if all went well and they hadn’t yet alerted the enemy, they would have to find a defensible position and prepare for the ceremony.  Cruzaz Ror had acquired a relic called the Circlet of Mists, an ancient construct that gave access to other planes and realities.  Ror’s purpose was the fulfillment of prophecy, the summoning of a god.<br>
<br>
It seemed like hours before the dwarf’s efforts were rewarded by the almost silent snick of a locking mechanism and the faint grating of stone on stone that seemed as loud as thunder.  Returning the hammer to his eager hands, Fastag crouched low and led the way in searching the blackness beyond with his dwarven vision.<br>
With a wave of his hand signaling all clear, the others followed.  Jillian ran a gloved hand across the stonework as she followed the dwarven priest in, noting that the walls were dry and clean, as if the passage had never been exposed to the wet air and fog of the forest.  Carlan was next, bending low to clear the opening he realized that though the passage was built by dwarves, its ceiling was almost six feet high.<br>
<br>
Stonepriest Dalgoth came after the young man, his thoughts only on the ceremony he would lead, leaving his personal safety in the hands of Miles Harden, the warrior who would willingly protect him even at the cost of his own life.  The inner turmoil that had been driving Miles to the edge of his sanity had disappeared within moments of his entry into the secret passage.  Stone walls, no matter how dark and dusty nor where they led, were something solid he understood and his mind quickly shifted to the task at hand.<br>
In the rear was Bryan who, like Fastag, would assist Dalgoth in the ceremony.  His thoughts were on the consequences of failure and all the good people whose lives depended upon their success.<br>
Such thoughts weighed heavily upon all in the little band as they made their way through a maze of passages and tunnels, each seeming to twist upon itself at impossible angles. Time and time again the party came to a sloping passage or stone stairway that led them deeper below the temple.  Led unerringly by the dwarf’s senses and stone knowledge, just as all thought themselves hopelessly lost, they came to a dead end that with a few touches in the right places, opened into a small, empty corridor.<br>
“Evil is near,” Dalgoth whispered, the first words spoken by the High Priest since they left the tree line.<br>
<br>
The band rounded a corner and, as if in answer to the high priest’s words, the dim orange glow of reflected torchlight appeared far down the passage, and a low, chanting murmur could be heard.<br>
“This is close enough,” whispered the High Priest.  “Stone Guardians,” now speaking to Jillian and Miles.  “Keep us safe…at least until the ceremony is complete.  We must finish before the priests of the Dark God conclude their summoning or all will be lost.”<br>
Receiving silent acknowledgement from the two warriors he looked to the young cleric.<br>
“Carlan, you must keep us secure from the creatures that may be sent against us.  May your faith be as stone my son.”<br>
“And yours as granite, Stonefather,” the young man said in reply as he gripped his holy symbol even tighter.<br>
<br>
Bryan and Fastag began creating a circle of protection around them and the high priest by spreading a thin line of obsidian and diamond dust from a small crystal cruse.  He laid another circle, larger than and encompassing the first, around the remaining three members of the group.<br>
Dalgoth began placing candles of gray, hard tallow at eight equally spaced points around the inner circle.  Once laid, he lit them with quiet words of magic until eight points of light cast flickering shadows on the stone walls.  Digging into the pack again he pulled a small platinum censure and a large, leather bound tome and set them before him as he kneeled on the cold granite floor.<br>
Lighting a small, white stick of incense, the High Priest motioned for his two fellows to kneel by him and join hands.  Placing the burning incense in the censure he grasped Fastag’s hand with his right hand and Bryan’s with his left.  Closing their eyes they began a quiet chant.<br>
The heavy atmosphere of evil lifted from around them.  The small band’s burden of depression and sadness was lifted from their souls, and they steeled themselves for whatever was to come.<br>
<br>
The Circlet of Mists stood upright in the center of the great chamber.  Already, a light mist rolled through its circular opening and darkness played from the depths of the portal.  Cruzaz Ror stood before the stone ring, arms raised and eyes closed.  His chanting echoed throughout the chamber.  Surrounding Ror and the Circlet were his acolytes and the undead minions who served him.<br>
<br>
The murmuring chant of the summons was interrupted by a roar of anger coming from both the Circlet and Ror himself.  Such a display of anger was common with the tall, gaunt man.  However the sound that issued from his mouth was no sound a human could ever voice.  Instantly, lesser servants of the Black God began sending out the undead creatures to find the cause of the disturbance they all felt.<br>
Silently, the decaying remains of humans and humanoids alike shuffled down the many passages throughout the temple.  Unseeing eyes moved in empty, rotting skulls as the creatures slowly, yet unerringly sought the cause of the interruption.  Moving more swiftly, passing the zombies, came the loathsome ghouls, cunning and cruel beasts whose twisted forms barely resembled the humans they once were.  Fiends long dead, pale things with fangs that could tear carrion or live flesh with equal viciousness loped down dark corridors.  Great white eyed brutes, barely humanoid, with flesh as dense as rock defiled the stone of the temple by passing through the walls as if they were water.  These and creatures far worse searched for the disturbing presence of good that had invaded their domain.<br>
<br>
A faint, golden mist issued from the mouth and nostrils of the Dwarven High Priest just as a hunched figure entered the hall.  Upon seeing the object of its hunt it leaped eagerly toward the party, green spittle running down its chin in anticipation of the soft flesh it smelled.<br>
Standing slightly apart, the two Guardians took defensive positions with swords at the ready, waiting to see if the circle of protection would hold.<br>
Cruzaz Ror continued his chanting as the mists roiled like a living thing.  A sickly mauve light lit the mists from deep within the gateway.<br>
<br>
Leaping for the closest two living beings, the ghoul was brought to an abrupt halt just short of its goal and with a shriek of frustration, recoiled from the barrier of protection surrounding the fleshy creatures.<br>
Miles and Jillian allowed each other a brief smile at the ghoul’s frustration but their satisfaction was short lived as four more of the foul creatures appeared.  One of these, unlike his drooling, gibbering fellows, had eyes that revealed an intensely evil intelligence.<br>
<br>
The gold mist slowly thickened and swirled until it entirely hid the three priests in the inner circle from view.  Carlan, mesmerized briefly by all that was taking place, was startled into action.  Grasping his god’s symbol, Carlan held it out towards the ghouls and chanted the words he hoped would turn away the undead creatures,  “Vile beasts of death and darkness turn away from the faithful servants of stone, turn from T’ro’adon.”<br>
The symbol of the hammer engulfed in flame flashed briefly with a low, fiery light.  Two of the ghouls shrieked in frustration and scrambled off into the darkness.<br>
The one, ghoul-like creature didn’t flinch.  “Nasty white fleshy thing cannot scare off I so easy,” said the ghast in a maddeningly high pitched voice.  “Our powers strong here,” it shrieked even as it moved closer, sensing the circle of protection.  “We are strong, we are many.  Soon Deathfather will be here and we will taste your flesh.”<br>
<br>
Carlan raised his symbol again, ready to attempt another dismissal.  A gray hand shot downward, into the circle of protection.  Its gray, stony flesh emerging from the ceiling above Carlan and grabbed his shoulder in a crushing grip.  Bones shattered and a cry of dismay and pain came from the young priest.<br>
Turning quickly at the cry, Jillian witnessed in horror the head of a creature emerge from the rock itself and clamp fierce fangs into the young man’s arm, then with a vicious twist of its head snapped the bone.<br>
With a scream of rage the young warrior raised her sword and struck at the wight’s head.  Steel bit into stony flesh as long claws raked across the dying priest’s face exposing bone and muscle.  Releasing the mutilated man, the creature dropped from the ceiling, ignoring the circle’s magic and advanced on the Stone Guardian.<br>
<br>
As the wight crossed the barrier of protection it failed and the ghouls and ghast began cautiously advancing toward Miles.  The warrior stood ready, his bastard sword glowing softly with its enchantments as he bounced it lightly in his mailed grip.<br>
“Fleshy thing not protected now,” said the ghast as it crossed the first circle. “Do fleshy things taste good I wonder?”<br>
The mist inside the inner circle was now a solid mass as it swirled in a silent gale.  No chanting could be heard from the priests within.<br>
<br>
In the chamber, the Circlet of Mists was now glowing brightly and a hot, foul breeze could be felt flowing from beyond.<br>
Claws narrowly missed Jillian as she thrust her long sword at the gray wight and sliced open its side.  The other clawed hand raked across her chest, opening her mail and slicing deep furrows in her skin and muscle.  When the thing struck her she felt the life flow from her body briefly and only then did she remember the stories of the deadly wight.  The weakness left her barely able to block the blows of the creature and she backed up to where Miles stood.  Miles was busy fending off the two ghouls and ghast.  Deep cuts across his face and legs had left him weakened and struggling to defend himself.  A final swing left one ghoul dead, yet he knew there would be others.<br>
<br>
The thick mist grew still.  The chanting peaked, then stopped.  Silence filled the chamber as Cruzaz Ror slowly lowered his arms.  The energies of the High Priest and his acolytes focused on the Circlet as a lazy ripple formed in the center of the mist.<br>
The two Guardians could barely lift their blades as the undead moved in, the smell of victory and sweet, living flesh at hand.<br>
The mist began circling the center of the Circlet.  A vortex formed and spiraled inward.  Deep within the depths of the whirlpool a dark form appeared.<br>
<br>
A wave of warm air wafted past the two exhausted warriors.  They looked back to see the gold mist explode outward like a hurricane, though they felt only a breeze.  The mist expanded, moving through air and stone, engulfing and destroying each of the creatures closing in upon the faithful defenders.<br>
Undead howled even as they turned to dust, acolytes bolted and ran in all directions, another supernatural scream of fury came from both Ror and the gateway as they were overcome by the cleansing gale.<br>
Ror was flung backward like a child’s doll.  The form beyond the gateway disappeared and the swirling mists vanished with a thunderous roar.<br>
<br>
“We are leaving NOW!” cried Dalgoth.  Grabbing the censure and book, he began running in the direction they had come.<br>
“We can’t leave Carlan,” yelled Jillian.<br>
Fastag stopped.  Hefting the lifeless man across his broad shoulders said, “Indeed it would not do to leave so faithful a Stoneson to this vermin.  Come girl, move those feet.  The unliving will gather again, for the ceremony will not have reached them all.”  The Dwarf turned and pushed on down the passage.<br>
Dalgoth, knowing stealth was not possible, lifted his symbol and murmured a few words causing it to glow with a dim, torchlight.<br>
Unerringly tracing their steps back, they came to the hidden doorway they had left ajar.  The pale face of a zombie appeared from the opening with others pushing from behind.  Holding out his symbol of the hammer and flame Dalgoth said simply, “By T’ro’adon, begone!”  The zombie instantly turned to gray dust, clearing the way for the party.<br>
<br>
Outside, as the five made their way across the clearing, the ground burst before them.  The skeletal remains of humans, dwarves and great beasts answered the call of the still living Cruzaz Ror.<br>
Miles tripped across the great bones of a giant as it rose from the ground and grabbed him by the legs.  Swinging his bastard sword around he sheared off the top of the thing’s skull, but before he could lift his blade for another attack, the giant lifted him in the air and flung him into the wall of the temple.  A dark stain appeared where his head met stone.<br>
“Miles, NO!”<br>
The giant turned empty eyes toward the girl and lumbered forward.  Bryan grabbed Jillian as she turned to run back, “Leave him, it’s too late!”<br>
“NO. No, not him too!” she cried, a mad look on her face.<br>
“Unless you want to join him we have to go!”  Not waiting for an argument he grabbed her arm and dragged her along until he felt her ripped from his grasp.  Turning, he saw her face down on the ground, fingers clawing at the dirt as a dozen rotting, skeletal hands dragged her down, into the soil.  Jillian was screaming insanely as she fought to keep herself from being buried alive.<br>
<br>
Bryan swung his hammer again and again at the corpses, crushing their bones into dust, but more burst from the ground to replace those destroyed.  He grasped her hands and pulled, urging her to hang on, but the supernatural strength of the hands continued to drag the woman down.  Even as he dug his heels in to give him leverage, more corpses burst through the soil.  Hands grasped and clawed at his legs, pulling him off balance and causing him to loose his grip.<br>
“Jillian!”  He broke free and lurched forward, trying to grasp her hands.  Their fingers touched briefly.  Then, she was gone.  “JILLIAN!”<br>
A huge ivory fist impacted inches from his face.  Bryan rolled away, breaking free of the grasping hands and pushed himself up.  The giant turned and raised its fist to strike again.  Bryan only spared a brief glance at the ground where the Stone Guardian had given her life before sprinting off after the remaining members of his band.<br>
<br>
Bryan found Fastag as the dwarf was crashing through the brush.  The dwarf was limping badly and one arm hung limply at his side.  He saw the shaft of an arrow protruding from the dwarf’s shoulderblade.  Dalgoth was nowhere to be seen.<br>
“Fastag!  Fastag!  Where is Dalgoth?”  Bryan grasped the dwarf’s good arm and lent him speed through the bush.  “Where is-“<br>
“DEAD!”  Fastag roared.  “Dead…like all tha others.  As we will be if we do not keep movin'.”<br>
<br>
